reconciled with modernity,logic,  reason, and science are fit<br>
to survive in the modern world. All other religions  deserve nothing but total extinction. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uarkuunaves.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ArkuunAves</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/16/02 7:18:58 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=292.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Religion is the Problem: Part 2</span><hr size=1> A few simple observations after reading a lot of these messages:<br>
<br>
1) The &quot;survival of religions&quot; would tend to be self-selecting, in my humble opinion.  Humans would have a lot less to do with this process than the supernatural being(s) that truthfully rule the universe.<br>
<br>
2) I'm unsure as to the ages or scientific/theological credentials of people here.  I notice &quot;analysis&quot; and &quot;scientific documentation&quot; from people that clearly do not have factual background data in what they are talking about.  Perhaps we should not all jump to claims of being an expert on something we don't even yet have a degree in? Much less years of industry experience?  I'm currently employed at a nuclear power plant for the summer, working an internship, and in the middle of getting a degree in Nuclear Engineering.  I do not presume to know for a certainty most of that which I have only read.<br>
<br>
3) Basic comments on this religion debate.  I myself was raised Catholic, then grew into an Agnostic and Atheist phase, alternating back and forth between these two ideologies.  Were I to categorize myself now, I would probably say Christian, tho I sometimes feel I'm undeserving of such.  The main point I wish to bring up is that whilest I will respect people who wish to make points about relgion, they must be willing to back up their points with logical argument and fact, rather than making blanket statements and then just saying &quot;well how do you know...&quot; or &quot;what if...&quot;.  There exists various archeological evidence supporting religious ideas of various religions, not even just Christianity.<br>
<br>
It strikes me that many people here seem to be speaking, indeed shouting, just so they are heard.  They make statements that are outlandish and contradictory to others' beliefs, without any evidence or background in such matters, because they know it will elicit responses from those who disagree.  If you like to argue for arguments' sake, then by all means continue.  If you'd like to have an actual discussion, where you have an open mind to perhaps being exposed to things you had not perviously considered that might alter your viewpoint, let me know.  Serious and mature people only, thank you.<br>
