      Neither are we, in most cases. This is a grassroots organization founded on the principle that ordinary, intelligent people are capable of understanding the relevant issues, and of formulating a valid set of opinions about those issues. The arguments advanced here will stand or fall on their own merit. Most of us have a low opinion of argument from authority, which is the ultimate result of an excessive concern with credentials. <br>
     Some of the most astute participants here are high school students and college undergraduates. Others are engineers and technicians with many years of experience in the nuclear industry. One is a retired Army officer with extensive experience in practical rocketry. This person is now a professor of geophysics at a major university, and also happens to be my humble self. I seldom refer to these credentials for a couple of reasons, one being that I actually know less about this specific subject than some of the dedicated and highly intelligent lay people who have researched it for many years, and whose efforts are the driving force behind this organization. More importantly, it is  contrary to the fundamental principles of science to base an advocacy position  primarily on appeal to one's own authority.<br>
     Being able to know the truth is not the same as knowing the truth, and knowing the truth is not the same as telling the truth. Facts and logic will carry the argument, regardless of who is advancing them. If the village idiot is right, and I am wrong, my degrees will not change that. <br>
     This is important because our primary objective is to change public attitudes and scientific policy. The general public is skeptical of appeals to scientific authority, as they should be; because, again, science is not about authority and credentials, and national policy certainly should not be.       <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A> at: 7/16/02 2:10:57 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uarkuunaves.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ArkuunAves</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/16/02 2:38:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=292.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: credentials</span><hr size=1> 1) Quite honestly I intended for my post to be taken largely within the context in which it was posted, being under a thread about religion.  I gave a technical reference which I perhaps shouldn't have, but please read my original post as being aimed towards people who have not attempted to understand the religions they are commenting on.  How about this:  I studied Buddhism in school passingly, but do not presume to know enough about it to call it a pointless faith with a bunch of followers that are brain-washed zombies following antiquated beliefs that will get them no where.  I pose that simply as an example of what can't be said in discussions like this; to be able to comment on something, you should at least have tried to learn about it and understand it.<br>
