2)On a scientific level: Whilest I think the opinion of everyone should be considered , those qualified to make comments (or who will at least qualify the statements they make) seem to make much more valuable contributions to discussions in my opinion.  I would first point out that credentials and authority are two different things, as you must know from the Army. I never said anything of someone's authority, I only said they should have a background in the area(credentials being a way of measuring a certain amount of knowledge having been gained). Plenty of people have credentials that those in authority do not have and would perhaps be better off having.  Regardless of that though, I will grant you that neither authority nor credentials are essential parts to one's intelligence.  Knowledge is, however; short of knowledge, only an incredible intellect will suffice.  I myself am an undergrad with what I think are ideas at least worth considering when it comes to some technical areas; when I make comments on these areas, however, I present whatever information I can to try to back up my statements with other accepted theories or operating experience.<br>
<br>
